The hyperbola

The standard form of the hyperbola is denoted (a) in the figure below. This has standard equation

\[{x^2\over a^2}-{y^2\over b^2}=1.\] The eccentricity, \(e\), is defined by \[e^2=1+{b^2\over a^2}\qquad e\gt 1).\]

Note the change in sign compared to the equivalent expressions for the ellipse. The lines \(y=\pm \dfrac{b}{a}x\) are asymptotes to the hyperbola (these are the lines to which each branch of the hyperbola approach as \(x\rightarrow \pm\infty\)).

If light is emitted from one focus then on hitting the hyperbolic curve it is reflected in such a way as to appear to be coming from the other focus. See (b) in the above figure. The hyperbola has fewer uses in applications than the other conic sections and so we will not dwell here on its properties.

Key Point

The standard equation of the hyperbola with foci at \((\pm ae,0)\) is \[\dfrac{x^2}{a^2}-\dfrac{y^2}{b^2}=1\qquad \text{with eccentricity}\ e\ \text{given by}\quad\ \ e^2=1+\dfrac{b^2}{a^2}\quad (e\gt;1)\]


General conics

The conics we have considered above - the ellipse, the parabola and the hyperbola - have all been presented in standard form:- their axes are parallel to either the \(x\)- or \(y\)-axis. However, conics may be rotated to any angle with respect to the axes: they clearly remain conics, but what equations do they have? It can be shown that the equation of any conic, can be described by the quadratic expression

\[Ax^2+Bxy+Cy^2+Dx+Ey+F=0\]

where \(A,B,C,D,E,F\) are constants.

If not all of \(A,B,C\) are zero (and \(F\) is a suitable number) the graph of this equation is

  1. an ellipse if \(B^2\lt4AC\)(circle if \(A=C\) and \(B=0\));
  2. a parabola if \(B^2=4AC\);
  3. a hyperbola if \(B^2\gt 4AC\).

Example

Classify each of the following equations as ellipse, parabola or hyperbola:

  1. \(x^2+2xy+3y^2+x-1=0\)
  2. \(x^2+2xy+y^2-3y+7=0\)
  3. \(2x^2+xy+2y^2-2x+3y=6\)
  4. \(3x^2+2x-5y+3y^2-10=0\)

Solution

  1. Here \(A=1,\ B=2,\ C=3 \qquad \therefore \quad B^2\lt 4AC\). This is an ellipse.
  2. Here \(A=1,\ B=2,\ C=1 \qquad \therefore \quad B^2=4AC\). This is a parabola.
  3. Here \(A=2,\ B=1,\ C=2 \qquad \therefore\quad B^2\lt 4AC\) also \(A=C\) but \(B\neq 0\). This is an ellipse.
  4. Here \(A=3,\ B=0,\ C=3 \qquad \therefore\quad B^2\lt 4AC\). Also \(A=C\) and \(B=0\). This is a circle.
